We are over the moon to introduce our next conference speaker 🌟GABRIELLE ROCK 🌟@gabriellaspmu who will be presenting her life changing technique CLEFT LIP BLUSHING 💉 

Gabrielle has been a PMU artist for over 8 years.
Whilst brows and lips are her biggest strength, she specialises in Cleft Lip tattooing.

This technique is a self-taught advanced technique, using both lip colours and camouflage colours to restore the cupids bow. Gabrielle tattooed her first set of cleft lips around 5 years ago, and since then has trialed & errored her technique to achieve perfection! 

Gabrielle started PMU when she was just 18 years old! She was also a 1st place winner of the UK PMU conference in 2019, as well as 2nd place World Championship winner at a Microblading conference in Amsterdam. 

This technique will give you a unique skill set that will be able to help transform the lives of SO many with a cleft palate!

A few Pre Draw Tips ✨✏️

I absolutely love when I have a set of lips that lacks a central project

Let’s take a look at the 2nd image…

1st - we made the ‘dip’ in her Cupid’s bow slightly more centre to the rest of her face.

2nd - we made both ‘peaks’ of the Cupid’s bow a lot tighter and closer together . This means that we over line more so in the centre of the lips and do not put any focus into the sides of her lips (as this will only make her Cupid’s bow appear very wide and dragged out. 
(In extreme cases like this, I may also carry out ‘underlining’ the lips aswell as overlining to ensure that the projection goes in the right places).

The 3rd image shows how my client has now  more projection in the centre of her lips, and how she is more likely to fit into a ‘rounded’ shape rather than an ‘oval’ shape ❤️

All my girls that have attended my masterclasses should know EXACTLY what I’m talking about 🥰😉

It truly saddens me to write this, and to be totally honest, I really didn’t want to even publicly post this - I suppose it makes it less real by keeping it private. 
But I cannot face going back to work and back to normality and being asked questions from those who do not know. 

My beautiful mum sadly passed away on 8th February. 💔
And I’m not going to go into it because it’s just too f*cking sad and I know my mum wouldn’t want to be remembered by how she passed away but more so how she was when she was still here. - you only have to look through these videos and pictures to see just how free-spirited and adventurous she was ❤️ 

So the only reason I’m coming on here to even say this is to give all my friends and clients that don’t know a little heads up. 
I know a lot of you know my mum through that time she worked for me as my PA (😂🤦🏼‍♀️) or just from how close we were so I know this will be very sad for a lot of you also 😢

Work related side note - I’m going to be back at work on 7th March.
Apologies to those I’ve had to cancel. - you will be booked back in as soon as I’ve had a couple weeks to settle into the new normality and I know where my heads at. Promise it won’t be another 6 month wait… I will get you in before that. 🤞🏼(I know you guys will be understanding ❤️)
In the meantime, please don’t feel like you can’t message me over your eyebrows or lips or training because I’m currently going through it. I have my wonderful Rosie who has still been working from home and doing the messages. 
So don’t worry…. You aren’t actually messaging myself so please don’t feel awkward.

If I can also ask that if you want to send any condolences, just maybe leave a comment instead.
I’ve figured that when I’m grieving… I ignore the majority of people 😬 and I know a lot of you will want to send me a message and check up on me and just know I really really really appreciate it.🙏🏼
But it’s easier for me to ‘like’ your comment in appreciation rather than private message you a reply.

Her funeral is Tuesday 28th feb, 11am at St.Anthony’s Church, Scotland road. (I know a lot of people on here knew & met my mum - you are more than welcome to attend).🕊️🤍

Combination brow 🔥
Combination brows definitely give the most realistic effect 😍

One of my favourite things to do is to correct a rounded brow 🔥- probably because it’s to easy!

If you’re struggling to correct a rounded brow.. here’s a few tips:

- firstly, the brows will more than likely be at their highest point from the years of over plucking. So ultimately you do not want to be adding anything that is above the brow.

- the best place to add thickness is just underneath the bulb. (Front) Making sure you don’t drop it too low as you do not want the brows to ‘point downwards’. This is ultimately the first thing that will straighten out the brow.

- the highest point of the brow (whether it is in the middle of the brow or if it is on the arch) will be the maximum height you take the arch too.
So find the highest point of the brow and use that as your reference to place in your arch. 
When placing your arch, try not to create anything too sharp. There’s a difference between ‘straightening out a rounded brow’ and ‘sharpening a rounded brow’. And you simply want to straighten… so ensure that your arch still remains soft and rounded as this will not make the overall brow still a ‘round shape’.

- the lowest point of the bulb, and the finishing point of the tail should be pretty much on the same level (the tail can drop lower by 1-2mm). I like to draw the tails of the brow ‘out’ rather than ‘down’ as it gives the eyes such a lifted appearance.  It can be quite difficult to ‘lift’ if the client has a lot of natural brow hair (that aren’t strays) that point ‘downwards’; so in order to avoid tweezing them away, ensure that the underneath of your arch does not come up too high. - the flatter and softer this underneath point is, the more lift you are able to get on the tail without having to tweeze natural hair away.  if the underneath of your arch tucks up quite high, then you will have to follow that point to lift the brows, which will result in having to tweeze out a lot of natural brown hair (not good).

- because rounded brows are usually shorter (length) then your typical brows, you will want to bring the fronts closer together.
Be mindful that you don’t overcompensate.
The ratio of the brows should be: arch to front = 2:3 … arch to tail - 1:3

Combination brow ✨

When doing any brows that are:
- quite sparse/gappy
- naturally coarse hairs 
- have distinctive stop/start placements in areas there should be hairs. 
- cover up of old PMU 

… then the combination brow is MANDATORY (sorry 😂) 

Combination involves using 2 different techniques and 2 different tools.

Firstly, I use microblading to create ultra fine crisp hairstrokes. 
Because these lines are so thin, they make really good ‘gap’ fillers. 

Secondly, I use the machine to create hairstrokes with a different texture.
I will choose to reinforce some hair strokes originally created with the blade. And also shade in some areas to help transition the natural brow to the new brow 😍

🔥🔥🔥Realistic combination brow🔥🔥🔥

The most brows 3D brows I think I’ve ever done 😍
(Swipe to see microblading vs combination, and also HEALED after 1 session!)

👉🏼𝐌𝐢𝐜𝐫𝐨𝐛𝐥𝐚𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐯𝐬. 𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐛𝐢𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧👈🏼

You can see on the 4th picture there is an image of microblading vs combination. 

Although my client did not NEED to have combination style (like my client did in the previous post), it was more of a person preference.

In cases like this where I use microblading to create ultra fine hairstrokes that blend seamlessly with the natural hair, I will let the client know that it is not MANDATORY to have combination brows and that it is my personal preference to go ahead and use some machine work.

(Combination is only mandatory when the natural brows are:
- quite sparse/gappy
- naturally coarse hairs 
- have distinctive stop/start placements in areas there should be hairs. 
- cover up of old PMU)

However, in this case, I decided to add the tiniest bit of shading over select hairstrokes to create a little more density and a little more 3D effect 🪄
From the picture, it will be quite hard to tell unless you are a PMU artist. But if you zoom in, you will see that some strokes have been made more dense, and also thicker - which is something you cannot do when using the microblade as it can be damaging to skin and will make results heal blurry.

👉🏼How combination is done 👈🏼 (simple version).

Once I have all my microblading hairstrokes in place, I will then use a 1RL 0.25-0.30mm needle to pass through certain strokes, to slightly extend them either side. - this makes the overall shape go a lil bit thicker but then either end of each stroke is soft and pixelated.

Not only that but there is more depth in the body of the brow rather than microblading just looking a little blank.

✨Combining both microblading and machine will enable me to get my strokes thin as a microblade but 3D and fluffy like a machine stroke. ✨ - and therefore creating the most realistic looking eyebrow 😍😍😍

It is so so so important to know when to drop an arch, as adding ‘above’ a pre-existing high arch can make the end result look really harsh and fierce 🤨😘

Whoever thinks having lip blush is just ‘putting a bit of colour into lips’ you are sadly mistaken. 😂✨

When I carry out lip blush, I look at the clients shape.
For this particular client.. we needed to disguise the migration & asymmetry she had from filler.

When you look at the last image you can see that I chose to make the ‘sides’ of the lip a lot more straight rather than follow the natural curvature the client had.

This involved a tiny small amount of ‘underlining’ on the sides of the lips.
By straightening the sides of the lips this automatically took the appearance away from the migration and put the focus into the middle of the lips and not at the sides. - I also did the same for the bottom lip.

This made the lips look a lot more fuller from the middle making the sides look less ‘bulky’ and rounded.

👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼
And before any trolls comment saying ‘why didn’t you tell her to get them dissolved first?’… well that answer is simple.

The client has had lip filler for quite a few years. And any filler that hasn’t broke down in that time is probably there for the staying. And if she hasn’t already had them dissolved, then that clearly means she wasn’t too bothered with the way they looked and therefore isn’t going to start getting them dissolved & refilled. 

As an artist, I don’t really put any limit on what I can / can’t do. ✨

An in depth pre-draw was all it took to create an illusion of smaller and more symmetrical lips. 
If you are the type of person that only likes to see to clients that have perfect symmetrical lips then that says a lot about you.. not me.
